## Opinion and Conclusion

Based on the comprehensive evidence reviewed, it is clear that climate change poses a profound and multifaceted threat to human health. The impacts are not limited to physical ailments but extend deeply into mental health and social well-being, disproportionately affecting the most vulnerable populations globally.

The complexity and interdependence of these health effects demand an integrated approach combining climate mitigation, adaptation, and robust public health strategies. Prioritizing health equity and strengthening healthcare systems to respond to climate-sensitive health risks are essential.

Moreover, increasing public awareness by framing climate change as a pressing health issue can enhance engagement and motivate collective action. Psychological support services should be expanded to address the growing mental health burden, including eco-anxiety and trauma from climate disasters.

In conclusion, climate change is not only an environmental crisis but a critical public health emergency that requires urgent, coordinated, and sustained responses at local, national, and global levels to protect current and future generations.

